# Security and Secrets

## Token Storage

- NEVER store access tokens in plaintext on disk or in environment variables
  in production. Always use the `TokenStorage` interface (KMS, Vault, etc.)
- `InMemoryTokenStorage` is for development and testing only — document this
  clearly wherever it appears
- Token lifetime: access tokens ~1 hour, refresh tokens up to 90 days
- Proactively refresh at T-60s to avoid mid-request expiry:
  `if (tokens.expiresAt - Date.now() < 60_000) { await refresh(); }`
- Always revoke tokens on explicit user logout (`/v1/tokens/revoke`)

## OAuth / PKCE

- S256 code challenge ONLY — plain PKCE is not acceptable
- State parameter must be cryptographically random: `crypto.randomBytes(32)`
- PKCE verifier: 43–128 unreserved URI characters, generated with `randomBytes`
- NEVER log the authorization code, code verifier, or any token value
- NEVER embed client_secret in client-side code

## Secrets in Code

- No hardcoded `clientId`, `clientSecret`, or API keys — ever
- `.env` files for local dev only, never committed (enforce via `.gitignore`)
- Tests use environment variables or in-memory fixtures, never real credentials

## Webhook Verification

- ALWAYS use `timingSafeEqual` from `node:crypto` for HMAC comparison
- NEVER use `===` or `==` to compare signatures — timing attack vector
- Read the raw body as `Buffer` BEFORE JSON parsing:
  `app.use(express.raw({ type: 'application/json' }))`
- Reject requests where the body buffer cannot be verified

## TLS

- Never set `NODE_TLS_REJECT_UNAUTHORIZED=0` — not even in tests
- Never pass `{ rejectUnauthorized: false }` to fetch or undici options
- All production URLs are HTTPS only

## Logging

- Use the `Logger` abstraction, never `console.log` or `console.error`
- Never log raw HTTP request/response bodies that may contain PII or tokens
- Always log request IDs (`x-request-id`) to correlate errors in production
- Log level: `error` for unhandled exceptions, `warn` for retried requests,
  `info` for normal flow milestones, `debug` for request/response metadata
